==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Maya
<hw>Ma"ya</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧"y⟦aum⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Hindu Philos.)</fld> <def>The name (in Vedantic philosophy) for
the doctrine of the unreality of matter, called, in English,
<altname>idealism</altname>; hence, nothingness; vanity;
illusion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Hindu Philos.)</fld> <def>the Hindu goddess
personifying the power that creates phenomena.</def> <au>[RHUD]</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Hindu Philos.)</fld> <def>the power to produce
illusions.</def> <au>[RHUD]</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Maya</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Maya
<hw>Ma"ya</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧"y⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>prop. n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Maya</plw> or <plw>Mayas</plw>.</plu> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>the Indian people occupying the area of Veracruz, Chiapas, Tabasco,
Campeche, and Yucatan, together with a part of Guatemala and a part of
Salvador. The Maya peoples are dark, short, and brachycephalic, and at
the time of the discovery had attained a higher grade of culture than
any other American people. They cultivated a variety of crops, were
expert in the manufacture and dyeing of cotton fabrics, used cacao as a
medium of exchange, and were workers of gold, silver, and copper. Their
architecture comprised elaborately carved temples and palaces, and they
possessed a superior calendar, and a developed system of hieroglyphic
writing, with records said to go back to about 700 <sc>a.
d</sc>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>the language of the Mayas.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mayaca</ent>⟦br⟧
